doc.previous: Saint Lucia is a Commonwealth realm; Queen Elizabeth II is the Head of State, represented on the island by a Governor-General. Executive power, however, is in the hands of the Prime Minister and his cabinet.[5] The prime minister is normally the head of the party commanding the support of the majority of the members of the House of Assembly, which has 17 seats.[10] The other chamber of Parliament, the Senate, has 11 appointed members.
doc.after: Saint Lucia is a two-party parliamentary democracy. Five political parties participated in the 28 November 2011 General Election. Dr Kenny Anthony of the St Lucia Labour Party won eleven of the seventeen seats.
